We notice that the long_df has null values which is in the form of "?". Let's clean it.¶

In [12]:
#dropping NaN entries (ones with "?")
smoke_data = smoke_data[smoke_data['Smokes'] != '?']
smoke_data = smoke_data[smoke_data['Num of pregnancies'] != '?']
smoke_data = smoke_data[smoke_data['Number of sexual partners'] != '?']
smoke_data = smoke_data[smoke_data['First sexual intercourse'] != '?']

It is commonly known that cervical cancer tends to occur in older age women. However, this plot shows us most people in this dataset are in their twenties. The curve is skewed to the right.¶

The heatmap below shows a moderate correlations between Dx and Dx:HPV (having Cervical cancer and having HPV - 0.62) and Dx and Dx:Cancer (having Cervical cancer and other kinds of cancer - 0.67).¶

In [110]:
sns.heatmap(long_df[['Age','Number of sexual partners','Dx:HPV','Dx','Dx:Cancer', 'Hinselmann', 'Biopsy']].corr(),annot=True)
Out[110]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7faac3a9ca20>

However, there is a strong correlation between having HPV and having another type of cancer (0.89).¶

The test used to diagnose Cervical Cancer is Hinselmann most of the time. Biopsy is not so commonly used.¶

In [22]:

def to_int(x):
    return int(x)
smoke_data['Smokes'] = smoke_data['Smokes'].apply(to_int)
smoke_data['Smokes (years)'] = smoke_data['Smokes (years)'].apply(to_int)
smoke_data['Smokes (packs/year)'] = smoke_data['Smokes (packs/year)'].apply(to_int)

Conclusion: Even though there are strong correlations between some attributes from both datasets (both positive and negative), there isn't enough evidence to conclude that there is a clear/strong relationship between Cervical Cancer and Risk Behaviors.¶
